## Bugatti Veyron EB 16.4: A Symphony of Speed and Engineering Excess

The Bugatti Veyron EB 16.4, a name that still resonates with a certain *je ne sais quoi* in the automotive world, wasn't just a car; it was a declaration. A defiant roar against convention, a testament to what happens when unchecked ambition meets unfathomable resources. Born from the fertile, and perhaps slightly unhinged, imagination of the [Volkswagen Group](/Volkswagen_Group), and meticulously crafted in the hallowed halls of [Molsheim](/Molsheim), France, by the legendary [Bugatti Automobiles S.A.S](/Bugatti_Automobiles), this [mid-engine](/Mid-engine_design) [sports car](/Sports_car) redefined the very concept of automotive performance between 2005 and 2015. It was named, with a nod to racing heritage, after the formidable French driver [Pierre Veyron](/Pierre_Veyron), a man who knew a thing or two about pushing the boundaries.

The original Veyron wasn't merely fast; it was an event. Its top speed of 407 km/h (253 mph) was a figure that, for a while, felt more like science fiction than automotive reality. It was so preposterously impressive that it earned the title of "Car of the Decade" from the discerning, and often scathing, critics of the [BBC](/BBC) television programme [Top Gear](/Top_Gear_(2002_TV_series)), and even snagged their "Best Car Driven All Year" award in 2005. But Bugatti, it seemed, had a penchant for not resting on their laurels. The later Super Sport variant pushed the envelope further, becoming one of the fastest street-legal production cars ever conceived, with a staggering top speed of 431.072 km/h (267.856 mph). And for those who fancied a bit of open-air exhilaration, the Grand Sport Vitesse held the title of the fastest roadster, hitting an average of 408.84 km/h (254.04 mph). The torch of ultimate speed, of course, would eventually be passed to its successor, the [Bugatti Chiron](/Bugatti_Chiron), but the Veyron's reign was nothing short of epochal.

The Veyron’s aesthetic lineage was shaped under the watchful eye of chief designer Hartmut Warkuß, with the exterior artistry attributed to [Jozef Kabaň](/Jozef_Kaba%C5%88) of Volkswagen. The engineering prowess behind this mechanical marvel was largely steered by chief technical officer Wolfgang Schreiber. Even the auditory experience was considered, with a bespoke sound system meticulously designed and integrated by [Burmester Audiosysteme](/Burmester_Audiosysteme). This wasn't just about brute force; it was about a holistic, if excessive, approach to automotive excellence.

Bugatti, ever the showman, didn't stop at a single masterpiece. They peppered the Veyron's lifespan with a dazzling array of special variants, each more exclusive than the last. In a move that anticipated the personalization trends of today, Bugatti even offered a Veyron 16.4 Configurator on their website in December 2010, allowing prospective buyers to meticulously customize their exterior and interior hues. The Veyron's production officially wound down in late 2014, but the special editions continued to roll out until 2015, ensuring a dramatic, if drawn-out, farewell.

### Origins: From Concept to Concrete Marvel

The seeds of the Veyron were sown in May 1998 when [Volkswagen AG](/Volkswagen_AG) acquired the rights to the Bugatti name and brand. The objective was clear: to resurrect the marque and create a successor to the formidable [EB 110](/Bugatti_EB_110) that had graced the automotive landscape under previous ownership. This wasn't a case of simply tweaking an existing model; it was a complete reinvention, a grand ambition that manifested through a series of audacious concept cars.

Between October 1998 and September 1999, Bugatti, in collaboration with the design house [Giugiaro](/Italdesign), unveiled a trio of concept vehicles. Each boasted permanent four-wheel drive and were powered by Volkswagen's innovative [W18 engine](/W18_engine). The first, the EB 118, was a stately two-door luxury [coupé](/Coup%C3%A9) that debuted at the 1998 [Paris Motor Show](/Paris_Motor_Show). Following this was the EB 218, a more expansive four-door [saloon](/Sedan_(automobile)) presented at the [1999 Geneva Motor Show](/Geneva_Motor_Show). The third, and perhaps most telling, was the 18/3 Chiron, a sleek [mid-engine](/Mid-engine) [sports car](/Sports_car) that hinted strongly at the Veyron’s eventual form, showcased at the 1999 [International Motor Show](/International_Motor_Show_Germany) in Frankfurt.

But the W18 engine, while impressive, was destined to be a stepping stone. In October 1999, Bugatti presented a fourth concept, the EB 18/4 Veyron, at the [Tokyo Motor Show](/Tokyo_Motor_Show). This iteration, styled in-house under Hartmut Warkuß's direction, retained the mid-engine sports car configuration but foreshadowed a more potent powerplant. By 2000, a refined version, the EB 16/4 Veyron, was displayed at motor shows globally. This was the moment the true heart of the Veyron was revealed: the revolutionary four-bank WR16 engine, a configuration that would define every production Veyron. Even Walter de Silva, then head of [SEAT](/SEAT) design, was tasked with submitting a design proposal, though Warkuß's vision ultimately prevailed.

The decision to greenlight production was officially made by Volkswagen in 2001. The first functional prototype emerged in August 2003, remarkably close to the series production model, save for minor details. The journey from concept to showroom was fraught with engineering challenges, a testament to the Veyron's extreme performance targets, which repeatedly delayed its launch until September 2005. The name itself, Veyron EB 16.4, was a deliberate homage. "EB" honored the founder, [Ettore Bugatti](/Ettore_Bugatti), while "16.4" pointed to the engine's 16 cylinders and four turbochargers. And the "Veyron" moniker? A direct tribute to [Pierre Veyron](/Pierre_Veyron) and his triumphant victory alongside [Jean-Pierre Wimille](/Jean-Pierre_Wimille) in the grueling [1939 24 Hours of Le Mans](/1939_24_Hours_of_Le_Mans).

### Bugatti Veyron (2005–2011): The Genesis of a Hypercar

The original Bugatti Veyron EB 16.4 was a masterclass in automotive engineering, a car that dared to ask "what if?" and then proceeded to answer with breathtaking clarity. At its core lay an 8.0-litre, quad-turbocharged, [W16](/W16_engine) engine. Imagine two narrow-angle [V8 engines](/V8_engine) fused together, each cylinder boasting four valves, for a grand total of 64. This colossal powerplant, with its 86 by 86 mm (3.39 by 3.39 in) bore and stroke, displaced a monumental 7,993 cc (487.8 cu in).

The transmission was equally extraordinary: a 7-speed, computer-controlled [dual-clutch](/Dual-clutch) [automatic transmission](/Automatic_transmission) built by [Ricardo](/Ricardo_plc), capable of shifts in under 150 milliseconds. This wasn't the everyday DSG found in mainstream Volkswagens; it was a bespoke unit designed for the Veyron's unique demands. Drivers could opt for semi-automatic control via magnesium paddles or let the car handle gear changes entirely. Replacing this marvel of engineering? A cool US$120,000. Power was delivered to all four wheels through a [permanent all-wheel drive](/Permanent_all-wheel_drive) system featuring [Haldex Traction](/Haldex_Traction) technology.

The Veyron demanded specialized footwear, clad in [Michelin](/Michelin) [PAX](/Michelin_PAX_System) [run-flat tyres](/Run-flat_tyre) engineered to withstand its extreme velocities. A set would set you back US$25,000, and mounting them was a service reserved exclusively for France, costing an additional US$70,000. The car tipped the scales at 1,888 kg (4,162 lb), resulting in a power-to-weight ratio of approximately 530 PS per ton, according to Volkswagen Group’s figures.

Its dimensions were substantial: a wheelbase of 2,710 mm (106.7 in), an overall length of 4,462 mm (175.7 in), a width of 1,998 mm (78.7 in), and a height of 1,204 mm (47.4 in). The cooling system was a complex beast, featuring ten radiators: three for air-to-liquid intercooling, three for engine water cooling, one for the air conditioning condenser, one for the transmission oil, one for the differential oil, and one for the engine oil. Aerodynamically, it was a study in efficiency, with a drag coefficient (Cd) of 0.41 in normal conditions, dropping to 0.36 when lowered, and a frontal area of 2.07 m² (22.3 sq ft), yielding a drag area (CdA) of 0.74 m² (8.0 sq ft).

The W16 engine, as certified by [TÜV Süddeutschland](/Technischer_%C3%9Cberwachungsverein), produced a formidable 736 kW (1,001 PS; 987 hp) and an immense 1,250 N⋅m (922 lbf⋅ft) of torque.

#### Top Speed: Breaking the Sound Barrier of Asphalt

The Veyron's top speed was the stuff of legend. On April 19, 2005, German inspection officials at Volkswagen Group's private [Ehra-Lessien](/Ehra-Lessien) test track recorded an astonishing average of 408.47 km/h (253.81 mph). This feat was later replicated, albeit with a touch more drama, by [James May](/James_May) on [Top Gear](/Top_Gear_(current_format)), who reached 407.5 km/h (253.2 mph) on the same track in November 2006. May famously noted that at such speeds, the engine consumed an unbelievable 45,000 liters of air per minute – enough to sustain a human for four days. He also observed the Veyron's remarkable composure, contrasting it with the alarming vibrations often felt in other supercars at their limits.

However, accessing this stratospheric velocity wasn't a casual affair. For everyday driving, the Veyron was electronically limited to a more "sensible" 343 km/h (213 mph). To unlock the true potential, a specific "top speed mode" was required. This involved a ritual with a special key, initiating a series of checks to ensure both car and driver were ready for the ultimate assault on speed. Upon activation, the rear spoiler retracted, front air diffusers closed, and the car’s ride height was dramatically lowered.

#### Braking: The Art of Abrupt Deceleration

Bringing a car capable of such speeds to a halt is as critical as achieving them. The Veyron employed advanced braking technology, featuring cross-drilled, radially vented [carbon fibre reinforced silicon carbide](/Reinforced_carbon-carbon) (C/SiC) composite discs manufactured by [SGL Carbon](/SGL_Carbon). These discs offered superior heat resistance and reduced weight compared to traditional cast iron. The calipers, crafted from lightweight aluminum alloy by [AP Racing](/AP_Racing), featured eight pistons at the front and six at the rear. Bugatti claimed a maximum deceleration of 1.3 g on road tyres, with an [anti-lock braking system](/Anti-lock_braking_system) (ABS) integrated even into the handbrake for added safety.

Prototypes underwent rigorous testing, including repeated braking from 312 km/h (194 mph) down to 80 km/h (50 mph) without experiencing brake fade. The system was designed to handle this demanding cycle every 22 seconds. At speeds exceeding 200 km/h (124 mph), the Veyron's rear wing transformed into an airbrake, tilting to a 55° angle in 0.4 seconds during braking, providing an additional 0.68 g of deceleration – equivalent to the stopping power of a typical hatchback. Bugatti asserted that the Veyron could brake from 400 km/h (249 mph) to a standstill in under 10 seconds, covering half a kilometer in the process.

#### Special Editions: Bespoke Masterpieces

The Veyron's production run was punctuated by exclusive special editions, each a unique expression of Bugatti's commitment to craftsmanship and exclusivity.

*   **Bugatti 16.4 Veyron Pur Sang (September 2007):** Limited to just five units, this was the first Veyron to forgo paint, showcasing its exposed carbon fiber and aluminum construction.
*   **Bugatti Veyron Fbg par Hermès (March 2008):** A collaboration with the renowned French design house [Hermès](/Herm%C3%A8s), this model featured a luxurious bull calfskin interior. It was limited to four units, with a subsequent Grand Sport version produced in the same configuration.
*   **Bugatti 16.4 Veyron Sang Noir (May 2008):** A limited run of 12 units.
*   **Bugatti Veyron Bleu Centenaire (March 2009):** A singular unit created to celebrate Bugatti's centenary.
*   **Bugatti Veyron "Jean-Pierre Wimille", "Achille Varzi", "Malcolm Campbell", "Hermann zu Leiningen" (September 2009):** A series of four editions named after legendary Bugatti racing drivers, each paying homage to their respective legacies.

### Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport (2009–2015): The Open-Top Revolution

The desire for open-air motoring led to the creation of the Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport, unveiled at the 2008 [Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance](/Pebble_Beach_Concours_d%27Elegance). This [targa top](/Targa_top) variant was a testament to Bugatti's engineering prowess, incorporating extensive structural reinforcements to compensate for the absence of a fixed roof. Minor alterations were made to the windshield and running lights. Owners received two removable tops: a primary hardtop and a secondary, more rudimentary "umbrella" roof for inclement weather.

With the hardtop in place, the Grand Sport matched the coupé’s performance. However, without it, the top speed was electronically capped at 369 km/h (229 mph). With the temporary soft roof deployed, this figure dropped to a still considerable 130 km/h (81 mph). Production was capped at 150 units, with the first 50 reserved exclusively for existing Bugatti customers. Production commenced in the second quarter of 2009.

#### Special Editions of the Grand Sport: Artistry in Motion

The Grand Sport also received its share of exclusive treatments:

*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Sang Bleu (August 2009):** A unique, one-off model featuring a striking two-tone exterior of blue carbon fiber and polished aluminum.
*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport L'Or Blanc (June 2011):** A collaboration with the esteemed [Royal Porcelain Factory](/Royal_Porcelain_Factory,_Berlin) in Berlin, this single-unit creation was adorned with a thin porcelain layer on its exterior and interior, including the fuel filler cap, badges, and wheel center caps. Bugatti proclaimed it the "first automobile equipped with porcelain," though porcelain had seen limited use in earlier automotive endeavors.
*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport "Dubai Motor Show 2011" Special Editions (November 2011):** Three distinct variations were presented at the Dubai Motor Show, each showcasing unique color combinations: a bright yellow body with black carbon accents, a blue carbon and polished aluminum finish, and a striking green carbon fiber tone with polished aluminum.
*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Bernar Venet (December 2012):** A singular art car designed by French conceptual artist [Bernar Venet](/Bernar_Venet). Its exterior and interior were adorned with technical equations meticulously used by Bugatti engineers during the Veyron's development.

### Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Super Sport, World Record Edition (2010–2011): Apex Predator

The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Super Sport represented a significant evolution, a more potent and aerodynamically refined iteration of the original Veyron. Production was deliberately limited to just 48 units. The Super Sport’s W16 engine was boosted to an astonishing 1,200 PS (882 kW; 1,183 hp) at 6,400 rpm, with a colossal torque output of 1,500 N⋅m (1,106 lb⋅ft) available between 3,000 and 5,000 rpm. This enhanced power, coupled with a revised aerodynamic package, propelled the Super Sport to a verified top speed of 431.072 km/h (267.856 mph), reclaiming the title of the world's fastest production car upon its introduction. However, to safeguard the tires from disintegration at such extreme velocities, customer cars were electronically limited to 415 km/h (258 mph).

The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Super Sport World Record Edition was an even more exclusive iteration, limited to a mere five units. These cars featured distinctive orange detailing, orange wheels, and a special black exposed carbon body. Crucially, the electronic speed limiter was deactivated on these models, allowing them to unleash their full, unbridled potential.

#### Top Speed World Record: A Moment in Automotive History

On July 4, 2010, the world watched as Bugatti reclaimed its speed crown. [James May](/James_May), then a presenter for [Top Gear](/Top_Gear_(2002_TV_series)), piloted the Veyron Super Sport to 417.61 km/h (259.49 mph) at the Ehra-Lessien test track. Later that day, Bugatti's official test driver, [Pierre Henri Raphanel](/Pierre_Henri_Raphanel), with representatives from the [Guinness Book of Records](/Guinness_Book_of_Records) and the German Technical Inspection Agency (TÜV) in attendance, achieved an average top speed of 431.072 km/h (267.856 mph) over two runs in opposing directions. This extraordinary feat officially wrested the production car speed record from the [SSC Ultimate Aero TT](/SSC_Ultimate_Aero_TT). The record-setting average was derived from a first run of 427.933 km/h (265.905 mph) and a second of 434.211 km/h (269.806 mph).

There was a brief period of ambiguity surrounding the record's validity due to the deactivation of the speed limiter on the customer versions. However, after a thorough review involving external experts, Guinness World Records confirmed Bugatti's record on April 15, 2013, acknowledging that a modification to the speed limiter did not alter the fundamental design of the car or its engine.

### Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse (2012–2015): The Pinnacle of Open-Top Performance

The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse emerged as the ultimate expression of the Veyron's open-top capabilities, essentially a targa-top version of the formidable Super Sport. It inherited the Super Sport's uprated engine, producing the same immense 1,200 PS (882 kW; 1,183 bhp) and 1,500 N⋅m (1,100 lb⋅ft) of torque. This allowed the Vitesse to achieve the 0–100 km/h (62 mph) sprint in a mere 2.6 seconds. On public roads, its speed was electronically limited to 375 km/h (233 mph).

The Vitesse made its debut at the [2012 Geneva Motor Show](/Geneva_Motor_Show), with subsequent appearances at the [Beijing Auto Show](/Beijing_Auto_Show) and the São Paulo Motor Show later that year.

#### Special Editions and Legacy: A Fond Farewell

The Vitesse also saw a range of special editions, including:

*   **World Record Car (WRC) Edition (2013):** Limited to 8 units and priced at €1.99 million, these celebrated the Vitesse's record-breaking achievements.
*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse Le Ciel Californien (August 2012):** Inspired by the historic [Bugatti Type 37A](/Bugatti_Type_37A), this exquisite machine was priced at €1.74 million.
*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse "1 of 1" (August 2014):** A unique commission for a Singaporean customer.
*   **Bugatti Veyron 16.4 Grand Sport Vitesse La Finale (March 2015):** This marked the end of the Veyron's production run, a poignant final chapter finished in a reversed red and black carbon fiber scheme.

In 2013, Bugatti also introduced the "Bugatti Legends" series, a collection of six distinct Vitesse models, each limited to three units, celebrating iconic figures from the marque's history: [Jean-Pierre Wimille](/Jean-Pierre_Wimille), [Jean Bugatti](/Jean_Bugatti), [Meo Costantini](/Meo_Costantini), [Rembrandt Bugatti](/Rembrandt_Bugatti), "Black Bess" (homage to the [Bugatti Type 18](/Bugatti_Type_18)), and [Ettore Bugatti](/Ettore_Bugatti) himself.

#### Records on the Road and Track

The Veyron Grand Sport Vitesse also etched its name in the record books. Driven by Chinese racer Anthony Liu at Ehra-Lessien, it achieved a top speed of 408.84 km/h (254.04 mph), becoming the fastest open-top production sports car. Dr. Wolfgang Schreiber, then President of Bugatti, expressed his thrill at surpassing the 400 km/h mark with an open-top car, reaffirming Bugatti's technological leadership. Liu himself described the experience as "incredibly comfortable and stable," even at such extreme speeds, with the open-top allowing for an immersive engine sound without excessive wind buffeting.

